AGI&nbsp; - For many Americans what is manifesting in these minutes, or in the next hours, depends on the area, will be the first solar eclipse.
The total eclipse of the sun, a phenomenon that in the next few hours will cross North America, began in the middle of the Pacific Ocean and now begins to be visible in the valley of the Rio Grande, in southern Texas. Millions of Americans are waiting for the phenomenon that, according to scientists, is repeated every about 250 years.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
< < < > < > < > < > < > < < > < < > < < < > < < < < > < < > > > > > > > > < < < > > > > > < > > > > > > < > > > > > > < > > > > > > > > > > > > > < > > > > > > > < > > > > > > >  > > > > > < > > > > > > > > > < > > > > < > > > > > > > > > > > > > > < > > 
There is a "incognita meteo" factor, explains Cristian Ferradas, researcher at the NASA Goddard Space Flight Center's geospatial physics lab: "If the sky is not serene, we could see changes in the temperature and behaviour of animals while the phenomenon lasts, but we will not see the visual effect of the eclipse at 100%." According to the US weather service, "optimal observation conditions are unlikely due to the expected cloud. Today there will be high and thin clouds" and it is also expected that these increases right at the time of the eclipse. But, according to the expert, beyond the "view show" that represents for the general public, this eclipse is interesting from the scientific point of view to study relevant aspects related to the astro. "The outer layer of the solar atmosphere, called the crown, usually cannot be seen directly, so this eclipse represents a unique search opportunity," says the agency's space flight center scientist in the American city of Greenbelt (Maryland). NASA will take advantage of the opportunity to directly analyze this crown, without the need for intervention of large telescopes and specialized tools used to create artificial eclipses.
&nbsp;
<h2>Si parte dalla Texas</h2>
For LaVerne Biser is the thirteenth: at 105, Biser, who lives in northern Texas, witnessed the first phenomenon in 1963, along with his wife. "Once you see one - he told the local newspapers - you want to see them all." The couple stayed married for 73 years and witnessed twelve eclipses. The wife, Marion, died last year, so it's up to him to carry on the tradition. "It is sad that she cannot be next to me - she commented - but you have to enjoy the moment. And I don't want to miss this date for anything in the world." &nbsp;
&nbsp;
