Israel's attack on the Iranian embassy in Damascus increased the risk of a conflict with the Lebanese Shiite Hezbollah, the Allies of Tehran closer to the Jewish state, whose leader Hasan Nasrallah swore revenge. Since October 7, the date of the Hamas attack, the Hezbollah and the Israeli army have begun to exchange blows along the border between Israel and Lebanon. A barrel and response whose intensity is gradually increased. According to Middle East Monitor, the average is 100 missile launches per day. A significant figure, in light of the fact that the average was 120 daily rocket exchanges when in 2006 Israel and Lebanon were officially at war.
&nbsp;
In 2006, the action of the Hezbollah ended with the re-undertaking of a series of tactics previously unknown to the organization. Although crushed by Israeli military superiority, Shiite militias have revealed anti-tank defenses, ground attack strategies and the possibility of cyber sabotage. The fact that the 2006 conflict ended with the withdrawal of Israel from southern Lebanon, a result that no Arab state had obtained since 1948, allowed Nasrallah to sing victory on the stage of Lebanese politics. The tension climbed back to the stars, leaves room for a total war scenario between the two sides; a scenario that sees the Shiite militias much more prepared than 2006.
&nbsp;
The nucleus of Lebanese militias consists of an army that, between military and reservists, can count on about 100 thousand men: an infantry equipped with motorized means and rockets capable of hitting medium distance targets. Ground forces equipped with anti-tank means, weapons capable of drilling armored and, from 2006 on, according to Arab Center for Research and Policy Studies of Doha, a range of at least 19 types of remotely controlled missiles and not, including Russian manufacturing Kornets and American Tows. The tanks, of Russian manufacture and relatively dated (T54, T55, T72), are 'parked' in Syria to avoid Israeli air force attacks (airspace is controlled by Russia ndr).
&nbsp;
The armored do not constitute the diamond tip of the Shiite militias, as well as the air defense system represents the weak point of Hezbollah On the contrary, the Radwan brigades, elite troops that can count on a number of actuals between 2000 and 3000, specialized in operations beyond enemy lines and guerrilla tactics. In assessing the evolution of a total war Israel must take into account that the Hezbollah arsenal can count, always according to Arab Center for Research and Policy Studies, on about 65 thousand missiles capable of hitting within a radius of 200 kilometers and 5,000 missiles longer range.
&nbsp;
Pushing Hezbollah beyond the Litani River is a goal that would not put Israel safe from the risk of an attack. At the moment the army of the Jewish State seems to want to avoid the risk of having to reject a land raid from Lebanon. To curb Israel the growth of Hezbollah militias and arsenals, but also difficulties and length of intervention in Gaza. However, it is difficult to understand whether this balance will go ahead, even because the tension at Rafah leaves no sharpening of tension and another Israeli attack on the border like that of Damascus could cause serious consequences for the entire region.
