AGI -&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;A series of attacks in the area of the Zaporizhzhia nuclear power plant reopen the risk of a nuclear accident. "Three people were killed and three wounds in the Pologivskyi> district of Zaporizhia, wrote on social media the governor of the Ivan Federov region, while six other people were wounded following another Russian missile attack that hit an industrial plant in the southern city of Ukraine, added the governor. Another drone was shot down on the roof of the reactor number six of the nuclear power plant. The head of the International Atomic Energy Agency (AIEA) condemned the attack of a drone on one of the six nuclear reactors of the Zaporizhia nuclear power plant, controlled by Russia, in Ukraine.
&nbsp;
"This cannot happen," wrote general manager Rafael Grossi in a social media post, adding: "No one can take advantage or gain any military or political advantage from attacks on nuclear installations. That's not possible. The Kremlin continues to blame Ukraine for the attacks on the power station, defining them "very dangerous", but a high officer of the Ukrainian intelligence denied the involvement of Kiev. "We need to create a free zone around Zaporizhzhia>, the nuclear power plant represents an opportunity, but also a risk. It is good that the forces in the field do not fight around or inside the power station, we must avoid another Chernobyl, said the Foreign Minister, Antonio Tajani.
<div </div
&nbsp;
In recent weeks Russia has hit up to 80% of conventional power plants and half of Ukraine's hydroelectric power plants, in heavy attacks since the beginning of the war, according to Ukrainian Energy Minister German Galushchenko. "Up to 80% of thermal production has been attacked. More than half of hydroelectric production and a large number of substations," Galushchenko told reporters in Kiev. "This is the biggest attack on the Ukraine's energy sector" from the beginning of the war, said the Ukrainian minister, adding that he suspects that Russia has modified its weapons to use now drones and explosive missiles in Iranian style that cause more damage to every attack.
&nbsp;
And while Russian Foreign Minister Sergei Lavrov flies on a mission to Beijing, Kiev continues to appeal to allies to continue to militarily support Ukraine. "They are finishing missile stocks to counter attacks from the sky of Russian fighters, including the deadly laser-drive bombs," is the Ukrainian demand that continues to hope for the help of allies and counts on the $60 billion still frozen aid from the American Congress. But the Washington Post reveals Donald Trump's alleged secret plan to end the conflict if he was re-elected to the White House: Kiev, according to Trump plan, should yield Crimea and the entire Donbass in Moscow, reveals the newspaper. Disturbing perspective for Kiev.&nbsp;
&nbsp;

