AGI -
<span> A Boeing 737 aircraft from the U.S. company Southwest Airlines lost cover of one of its engines, which detached and hit the wing during take-off. The accident will investigate the Federal Aviation Administration.</span>
&nbsp;
The incident occurred at 8.15 local time on Sunday (14.15 GMT), when the plane, model 737-800, was due to return to the Denver International Airport, 25 minutes after takeoff. On board the plane, which was headed to Houston, there were 135 passengers and six crew members, who had no injuries.
&nbsp;
"We apologize for the inconvenience and delay, but our priority is maximum security for our customers and employees. Our maintenance teams are checking the plane," said the airline in a Sunday statement.
&nbsp;
The incident on Sunday is added to the list of problems of Boeing, the second world manufacturer of commercial aircraft.&nbsp; At the beginning of January 2024, a panel covering the space for an emergency door on a Boeing 737 Max-9 of Alaska Airlines took off shortly after the plane took off. The incident, which did not cause injury, triggered a series of new investigations into Boeing's operations.
&nbsp;
FAA has encountered dozens of quality control issues both at Boeing and its supplier Spirit AeroSystems, while another report from the National Transportation Safety Board (NTSA) revealed that the panel disconnected from the Alaska Airlines plane had not been installed properly and had no four fasteners.
The Boeing crisis began on 29 October 2018, when the Indonesian flight Lion Air 610 crashed into the Java Sea shortly after taking off, killing all 189 passengers.
On March 10, 2019, Ethiopian Airlines Flight 302 crashed into similar circumstances, killing all 157 people on board. These two incidents have led dozens of countries around the world to ban flights from family 737 aircraft.
&nbsp;

